Data sources

Data files - Crime_Data_from_2020_to_Present.csv

Date downloaded - September 14, 2023

Description - This data set contains crime reports from the city of Los Angeles dating back to 2020. This data is copied from original crime reports that were recorded on paper, therefore there may be some mistakes. Some missing data location fields are denoted as (0Â°, 0Â°). To ensure privacy, address fields are only provided to the closest hundred block.

Source of downloaded file - Itâs taken from the Data.gov website. Data.gov is the United States governmentâs open data website. It provides access to datasets published by agencies across the federal government. Data.gov is intended to provide access to government open data to the public, achieve agency missions, drive innovation, fuel economic activity, and uphold the ideals of an open and transparent government. https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/crime-data-from-2020-to-present

Original source - The original data source is provided by the Los Angeles Police Department on data.lacity.org/ website. https://data.lacity.org/Public-Safety/Crime-Data-from-2020-to-Present/2nrs-mtv8

Validity of data - Our data comes from an authentic source, the Los Angeles Police Department. According to the original source, the data collected has been transcribed from original criminal reports that are typed on paper, so there may be some mistakes in the data. We presume the data is biased because it was collected by the LAPD. The different factors involved in skewed data may include the time of day the crime happened, police employment, socioeconomic and racial bias, data entry errors, political and organizational pressure, data collection methods, and so on.


Evaluating proposal expectations

To demonstrate how the data is distributed, we summarized the idea of centrality for the variable victim_age. It appears that the median age is 37; if the median is 37, we know that half of the individuals in the data set are 37 years old or younger, and half are 37 years old or older.

df <- read_csv(here("data_processed", "clean_crime_data.csv"))

df %>% 
    filter(victim_age != 0) %>% 
    filter(victim_sex %in% c("M","F")) %>% 
    summarise( median = median(victim_age),
               mean = mean(victim_age),
               sd = sd(victim_age)) 
#> # A tibble: 1 Ã 3
#>   median  mean    sd
#>    <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
#> 1     37  39.8  15.5

We have also utilized factoring concept in this. We categorized offenses depending on the number of observations we have, with the remaining crimes falling into the âAll Other Crimesâ category. We used the boxplot data visualization technique to investigate the key association between data variables such as âvictim_ageâ and âgrouped_crimeâ. Box plots provide a visual representation of the median, quartiles, and potential outliers.

Summary Statistics: We calculated summary statistics for victim_age within each crime_name category. This will aid in understanding how the ages of victims differ for different sorts of crimes.

df1 <- df %>% 
    filter(victim_age >= 1 & victim_age <= 100) %>% 
  mutate(
    grouped_crime = fct_other(grouped_crime, keep = c(
      "Theft/Burglary", "Assault", "Vehicle Theft And Rule Breaks", "Vandalism",
      "Violation Of Rules", "Domestic Violence", "Shoplifting", "Weapons Possessions",
      "Fraud", "Sexual Assaults", "Child Abuse/Neglect", "Drug Offenses")),
    grouped_crime = fct_recode(grouped_crime, "All Other Crimes" = "Other"),
  ) %>% 
    filter(!(grouped_crime == "Child Abuse/Neglect" & victim_age > 18))   

View(df1)

ggplot(df1, aes(x = victim_age, y = grouped_crime)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Victim Age by Crime Name", x = "Victim Age", y = "Crime Name") +        theme_minimal()

Observations

  1. Median Victim Age: The median victim age is near the bottom of the age range. This means that the majority of victims are younger in a right-skewed distribution.

  2. Interquartile Range (IQR): The IQR is concentrated toward the younger end of the age range. This shows that the middle 50% of victims are often younger.

  3. Long Right Whisker: The right whisker (extending to the right) is longer than the left whisker. This indicates the presence of data points with higher victim ages, which are considered outliers or extreme values in this context.

  4. Potential Outliers: Potential outliers are more likely to be on the right side of the distribution in a right-skewed box plot. These outliers are incidents in which the victimâs age is unusually young in comparison to the majority of cases.

  5. Distribution Shape: A right-skewed distribution is characterized by a long tail extending to the right. This asymmetry in the distribution suggests that relatively fewer cases involve older victims, but there are some exceptional cases with older victims.

  6. Central Tendency: In right-skewed data, the mean victim age is usually greater than the median due to the influence of the right-skewed tail.

In summary, a right-skewed box plot for victim age and crime name suggests that the majority of victims tend to be younger, while there are relatively fewer cases involving older victims. As a result, we discovered support for the anticipated relationship described in our proposal.

df <- read_csv(here("data_processed", "clean_crime_data.csv"))

df %>% 
    filter(year %in% c(2020, 2022)) %>% 
    group_by(area_name, year) %>% 
    count() %>% 
    mutate(
        year = as.factor(year)
    ) %>% 
    arrange(year) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = n, y = fct_reorder2(area_name, year, desc(n)))) +
    geom_line(aes(group = area_name), color = 'lightblue', size = 1) +

    scale_color_manual(
      values = c('lightblue', 'steelblue')) + 
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        x = "Number of crimes",
        y = "Area Name",
        title = "Crime count in each area of Los Angeles",

    )

The graph above depicts the growing crime rates in Los Angeles neighborhoods from 2020 to 2022. According to the plot, the Central region has the highest crime rate, followed by 77th street and Pacific, and so on. So, these places must have increased police resources to improve crime prevention and community well-being.

Research question 3: What are the month wise trends in crime counts in Los Angeles for the years 2020, 2021, and 2022, and how do various factors influencing these trends over the three-year period?â

Cl_crime  <- read_csv(here("data_processed", "clean_crime_data.csv"))

# Define the order of months
months_order <- c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec")
 
# Filter data for each year and calculate monthly total crimes

crimes_2020 <- Cl_crime[Cl_crime$year == 2020,]
crimes_2020$month <- factor(crimes_2020$month, levels = months_order)
month_wise_2020 <- crimes_2020 %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(total_crimes = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(total_crimes))
 
crimes_2021 <- Cl_crime[Cl_crime$year == 2021,]
crimes_2021$month <- factor(crimes_2021$month, levels = months_order)
month_wise_2021 <- crimes_2021 %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(total_crimes = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(total_crimes))
 
crimes_2022 <- Cl_crime[Cl_crime$year == 2022,]
crimes_2022$month <- factor(crimes_2022$month, levels = months_order)
month_wise_2022 <- crimes_2022 %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(total_crimes = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(total_crimes))
 
# Combine data for all three years
combined_data <- rbind(
  transform(month_wise_2020, year = 2020),
  transform(month_wise_2021, year = 2021),
  transform(month_wise_2022, year = 2022))
 
# Reorder the months factor
combined_data$month <- factor(combined_data$month, levels = months_order)

#Finding the mean crime counts
#mean_crime_count <- mean(combined_data$total_crimes) 
#mean_crimes_2020 <- mean(month_wise_2020$total_crimes) 
#mean_crimes_2021 <- mean(month_wise_2021$total_crimes) 
#mean_crimes_2022 <- mean(month_wise_2022$total_crimes)
 
# Create the line graph with different colors for different years and without legend
ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = month, y = total_crimes, group = year, color = as.factor(year))) +

Expectation

Based on prior research, it was expected that crime rates would show seasonal fluctuation within a year with increases in summer and declines in winter. The data distributions support this - monthly totals spike in summer and drop in winter months consistently across the 3 years. It was also expected that 2020 would have lower crime than 2021 and 2022 due to pandemic suppression. The visualization supports this clearly - 2020 crime rates are lower than the other two years.

Key Insights

Seasonality of Crime : Within each year, Los Angeles displays a consistent seasonal pattern in crime rates, with spikes during the summer months from May to October, followed by declines in winter. This cycle corresponds with multiple factors that collectively make summer more conducive to crime. The warmer weather and increased outdoor activity from May to October generates multiple factors leading to consistently higher crime rates in Los Angeles during these summer months compared to the rest of the year. Firstly, warmer temperatures bring more people outdoors to public spaces, beaches and events, increasing interactions and providing more opportunities for crimes to be committed. In addition, school summer breaks lead to more teens and youth spending time outside with minimal supervision, which contributes to vandalism, petty crimes, fights, and gang violence. This idle time for youth exacerbates delinquent behavior. The summer season also sees a major spike in tourism and travelers to Los Angeles. The crowds of unfamiliar tourists represent prime targets for pickpocketing, thefts, robberies, and scams. Criminals can blend in easily to target victims. Criminals also take advantage of summer travel and vacations by targeting homes left empty, leading to spikes in break-ins and burglaries during this season.

Drilling down further, the data reveals an intriguing pattern of crime rates declining in September, only to spike upwards in October across all 3 years. September represents a stabilization following the summer peak, as schools reopen providing structure for youth, weather gradually cools while remaining mild, tourism dies down, police ramp up after summer, people return from vacations and seasonal jobs end. This convergence results in a dip in crimes. However, October then faces multiple transitions that disrupt the stabilization. The holiday shopping season also ramps up in October, with year-end inventory stocking up in stores combined with gift purchase pressures. This drives financially desperate individuals towards retail theft and robberies.

Yearly Variations in Crime Rates : In early 2020, the United States experienced the arrival of the COVID-19 pandemic, with the first confirmed case recorded on January 20. As the virus spread, it had a significant impact on various aspects of society, including crime rates in Los Angeles. During the initial months of the pandemic, from January to April, there was a notable rise in COVID-19 cases. This rise coincided with a decrease in reported crime cases, which is an unusual trend. However, in April 2020, there was a sudden spike in both COVID-19 cases and crime rates. This spike was followed by a drop in COVID-19 cases in May, but crime rates remained relatively high, making May the third month with the highest crime count in 2020. In the context of this rise in crime, there were significant incidents that drew national attention. One such incident was the tragic death of George Floyd, a Black man, in May 2020, due to police brutality. This incident was captured on video, leading to widespread protests across the United States, including in Los Angeles.

In 2021, there was an initial period of relative calm in terms of crime rates when compared to the previous year, 2020. This period of lower crime rates extended for the first half of the year. However, this trend drastically changed in the latter half of 2021. During these six months, crime rates rose significantly, surpassing the average crime rates for the entire year. Notably, October 2021 saw the highest crime rates for the entire year. A specific incident that gained significant attention and likely contributed to the surge in crime rates occurred on October 27, 2021. On this day, a Long Beach Unified School safety officer was charged with murder in the shooting death of an unarmed 18-year-old. This incident led to public outrage, protests, and strikes, possibly adding to the overall tension and contributing to the rise in crime rates for that month. Additionally, itâs suggested in the passage that the increase in crime rates during the latter part of 2021 might have been influenced by the ongoing effects of the COVID-19 lockdowns. As restrictions eased towards the end of July, there could have been a relaxation in social activities, leading to increased interactions and, potentially, more opportunities for criminal activities.

When considering the broader trend, crime counts in 2022 surpassed the mean crime counts of the previous years (2020 and 2021). This upward trend in crime rates over the years was influenced by various factors. Population growth played a role, creating a larger pool of potential offenders and victims. Additionally, the lingering impacts of the pandemic, such as economic disruptions, job losses, and mental health challenges, created an environment conducive to criminal activities. Other significant factors contributing to the rise in crime rates included decriminalization, which reduced the deterrence effect for certain offenses, California decriminalized some property crimes under $950 value. Early release of prisoners to mitigate COVID-19 spread in prisons, potentially leading to an increase in criminal behavior. Economic challenges, reflected in high unemployment rates and increased poverty, created desperation among individuals, driving some towards criminal activities. The surge in homelessness further exacerbated social issues, often linked to petty crimes.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the monthly crime data for Los Angeles from 2020 to 2022 reveals several key insights. A predictable seasonal pattern emerges, with summer months seeing spikes in crime driven by factors like weather, events, tourism and youth idleness. Within this pattern, October consistently experiences a peak compared to a stabilization in September as schools reopen and tourism declines. The data also highlights the significant impact of major incidents like the COVID-19 pandemic and protests on crime rates. 2020 saw lower crime during lockdowns, while reopening and unrest corresponded with 2021-2022 increases. Factors like population growth, economic anxiety, law enforcement budget cuts and decriminalization contribute to the general upward trend. More research integrating the multiple influences is needed. But this Los Angeles crime data analysis provides a model for dissecting seasonal, incident and societal drivers of crime.

Research question 4: What is the gender distribution of crime victims in Los Angeles, and is there a discernible trend or pattern in terms of which gender is more frequently victimized? Also, what are the top five crimes that occurred between 2020 and 2023, and how many victims were affected by victim sex?

df <- read_csv(here("data_processed", "clean_crime_data.csv"))

# Drop rows with "Unknown" ("X") values in the "victim_sex" column
filtered_crimes <- df %>%
    filter(victim_sex != "X") %>% 
    filter(!is.na(victim_sex)) %>% 
    filter(victim_sex != "-") %>% 
    filter(victim_sex != "H")

# Count the number of victims by sex
victim_counts <- filtered_crimes %>%
  count(victim_sex)
  
#plot showing which gender is mostly victimized (male OR female?) in a bar graph
custom_colors <- c("M" = "steelblue", "F" = "pink")

# Create a pie chart with values inside each slice
#plot showing which gender is mostly victimized (male OR female?) in a pie chart
ggplot(victim_counts, aes(x = "", y = n, fill = factor(victim_sex))) +
     geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
     coord_polar(theta = "y") +
     labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, fill = "Victim Sex") +
     theme_void() +
     theme(legend.position = "right") +
     geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(n / sum(n), accuracy = 0.1)),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 4, color = "black") +
     scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors)

# Save the ggplot to a file using ggsave
ggsave("figs/sexDistribution.png", width = 6, height = 4, dpi = 300)

Appendix

Description - The variables and their description of the data set are as follows:

DR_NO - Division of Records Number: Official file number made up of a 2 digit year, area ID, and 5 digits

Date Rptd - MM/DD/YYYY - The date of reported crime

DATE OCC - MM/DD/YYYY - The date of crime occurred

TIME OCC - MM/DD/YYYY - The time of crime occurred

AREA - The LAPD has 21 Community Police Stations referred to as Geographic Areas within the department. These Geographic Areas are sequentially numbered from 1-21.

AREA NAME - The 21 Geographic Areas or Patrol Divisions are also given a name designation that references a landmark or the surrounding community that it is responsible for.

Rpt Dist No. - A four-digit code that represents a sub-area within a Geographic Area.

Crm Cd - Indicates the crime committed.

Crm Cd Desc - Defines the Crime Code provided.

Mocodes - Modus Operandi: Activities associated with the suspect in commission of the crime.

Vict Age - Victim Age

Vict Sex - F - Female M - Male X - Unknown

Vict Descent - Descent Code: A - Other Asian B - Black C - Chinese D - Cambodian F - Filipino G - Guamanian H - Hispanic/Latin/Mexican I - American Indian/Alaskan Native J - Japanese K - Korean L - Laotian O - Other P - Pacific Islander S - Samoan U - Hawaiian V - Vietnamese W - White X - Unknown Z - Asian Indian

Premis Cd - The type of structure, vehicle, or location where the crime took place.

Premis Desc - Defines the Premise Code provided.

Weapon Used Cd - The type of weapon used in the crime.

Weapon Desc - Defines the Weapon Used Code provided.

Status - Status of the case. (IC is the default)

Status Desc - Defines the Status Code provided.

Crm Cd 1 - Indicates the crime committed. Crime Code 1 is the primary and most serious one. Crime Code 2, 3, and 4 are respectively less serious offenses. Lower crime class numbers are more serious.

Crm Cd 2 - May contain a code for an additional crime, less serious than Crime Code 1.

Crm Cd 3 - May contain a code for an additional crime, less serious than Crime Code 1.

Crm Cd 4 - May contain a code for an additional crime, less serious than Crime Code 1.

LOCATION - Street address of crime incident rounded to the nearest hundred block to maintain anonymity. Cross Street - Cross Street of rounded Address

LAT - Latitude

LON - Longtitude

crimes_of_interest <- c("Theft/Burglary", "Assault", "Vehicle Theft And Rule Breaks", "Vandalism", "Violation Of Rules")

crime_summary <- df1 %>%
    
  filter(
    year %in% c(2020, 2022),
    grouped_crime %in% crimes_of_interest) %>%
    group_by(grouped_crime, year) %>% 
    count() %>% 
    slice(1:5) %>% 
  mutate(
    # Reorder state variables
    grouped_crime = fct_reorder2(grouped_crime,
      year, desc(n)),
    # Convert year to discrete variable
    year = as.factor(year),
    
    # Make labels
    label = paste(grouped_crime, ' (',
                  round(n), ')'),
    label_left = ifelse(year == 2020, label, NA),
    label_right = ifelse(year == 2022, label, NA))


crime_summary %>%
    select(grouped_crime, year, n, label)

ggplot(crime_summary,
       aes(x = year, y = n,
           group = grouped_crime)) +
    geom_line() +
    # Add 1970 labels (left side)
    geom_text_repel(
      aes(label = label_left),
      hjust = 1, nudge_x = -0.05,
      direction = 'y', segment.color = 'grey') +
    # Add 2017 labels (right side)
    geom_text_repel(
      aes(label = label_right),
      hjust = 0, nudge_x = 0.08,
      direction = 'y', segment.color = 'grey') + 
    # Move year labels to top, modify line colors
    scale_x_discrete(position = 'top') +
    scale_color_manual(values = c('red', 'black')) +
    scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = c(0, 20000, 40000, 60000),
    expand = expand_scale(mult = c(0, 0.05))) + 
    # Annotate & adjust theme
    labs(x = NULL,
         y = 'Milk produced (billion lbs)',
         title = 'Top 10 milk producing states (1970 - 2017)') +
    theme(panel.grid  = element_blank(),
          axis.text.y = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks = element_blank(),
          legend.position = 'none') +
    theme_minimal_grid()
